areer","header":"Represented Milford fifteen times in the General Court","body":"He represented Milford in fifteen sessions of the Connecticut General Court between 1691 and 1703 — a span of sustained civic service that ran alongside his captaincy of the militia. His father Roger Newton Sr. had helped found the town's church."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Thomas Hooker left him £10 in his will","body":"He was nine months old when his grandfather Rev. Thomas Hooker died in 1647. Thomas's will left a £10 legacy to him — a substantial inheritance for a Hooker grandchild born during the Hartford founding."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"His wife and cousin's wife were Fenn half-sisters","body":"His wife Martha Fenn's half-sister Susanna married William Hooker — Samuel's first cousin. The Fenn family thus connected to the Hooker tree twice in the same generation through different lines."},{"number":5,"category":"family","header":"A second marriage to a soldier's widow","body":"After Martha Fenn died, Samuel married Sarah Welch Fowler, widow of John Fowler, who had been killed taking an Indian fort in 1693. Their son Abner bore a name found nowhere else in the Newton or Hooker line."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"career":[{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Court","start_year":1691,"end_year":1703,"notes":"Represented Milford in 15 sessions of the General Court, 1691-1703."}],"military_service":[{"war":"King Philip's War","war_id":"WAR002","rank_start":"Ensign","rank_end":"Captain","rank_year_start":1675,"rank_year_end":1698,"unit":"Milford Militia","notes":"Appointed ensign 1675 at outbreak of King Philip's War. Served in recurring skirmishes with Indians. Rose to captain of Milford militia 1698. Source: Newton Genealogy (Leonard 1915)."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Newton","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"documents":[],"slug":"samuel-newton-1646"},"X00097":{"id":"X0